). Physical examination and laboratory blood analysis revealed no other clinical pathology, and renal function was normal. The patient was not taking any prescription medications.
The patient had no history of seizures and was therefore eligible to receive high doses of penicillin G. After confirming that the patient was not allergic to penicillin (by administering a daily dose of amoxicillin for six days), the patient was started on a 21-day course of penicillin G and hydrocortisone (
) delivered via midline catheter infusion. This treatment course was recently postulated to be efficacious for treating dysphagia, dysarthria, and other ALS-related symptoms
.
